Why is it that unlicensed unregistered vehicles are allowed to be randomly parked on city streets and be moved from place to place under their own power and not subjected to immediate ticketing as long as they are moved every 72 hours or less? The fact that they are found parked in new locations should subject them to immediate impoundment under CA vehicle code (operation of unlicensed vehicles on public highways). Let's get these blight out of our neighborhoods (72 hour red tagging accomplishes nothing if the warnings are removed and the vehicle is DRIVEN to a new location after dark. E.g., white Cadillac last seen parked on Chesney between Alex & Gramsby and red Mazda SUV last seen parked on Rossatto -- two other vehicles have been reported to be similarly moving around the neighborhood and all are believed to be associated with the same individuals).

She reported it to her maintenance manager.This is a constantly-recurring problem throughout San Jose. The city needs a lighting inspector to curtail this egregious waste of electricity. If the lights need to be temporarily switched on in always-on mode for maintenance or to offset a controls issue, then it should be visibly posted in the area. Streetlights need ID numbers help expedite corrective action reports. These have none.

A black Mercedes convertible with the vanity license plate PD LAW nearly struck two pedestrians in the crosswalk at Calaveras and Park. The incident occurred on Oct. 11, 2010, at approx. 4:40 p.m. A mother and daughter were walking their bicycles across Park Ave. within the crosswalk. Vehicles in both directions of Park Ave. stopped to allow them to cross safely. The vehicle with the license plate PD LAW did not stop; instead, it veered into the bicycle lane, attempting to pass a stopped vehicle on the right, rather than waiting for the pedestrians to cross safely. A driver stopped at the intersection saw the Mercedes driving around and sounded his horn for an extended period; the Mercedes only stopped abruptly when it reached the crosswalk. According to a neighborhood listserv, the black Mercedes is regularly parked at the law offices of Dennis J.
